@@ -95,7 +95,7 @@
           "name": "Can I use retinol during pregnancy?",
           "acceptedAnswer": {
             "@type": "Answer",
-            "text": "No. Retinoids are not safe in pregnancy. Focus on strict sun protection during pregnancy; treat post-delivery."
+            "text": "Oral retinoids are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy. Topical retinoids have minimal skin absorption and aren't proven human developmental toxicants, but because large controlled pregnancy safety trials are lacking, most guidance still recommends avoiding them as a precaution (Chien et al., 2016) -- focus on strict sun protection during pregnancy and treat pigmentation post-delivery. See our full evidence review at opalradiant.com/blog/melasma-in-pregnancy-chloasma."
           }
         }
     ]
@@ -252,11 +252,11 @@
             </div>
             <div class="faq__item">
               <button class="faq__question" aria-expanded="false">Does pregnancy always trigger melasma?</button>
-              <div class="faq__answer"><p>About 50–70% of pregnancies trigger melasma. It can fade postpartum but often needs treatment for full clearance.</p></div>
+              <div class="faq__answer"><p>Not always, but pregnancy is one of the most consistent triggers: a global survey of 324 women with melasma found 26% reported onset during pregnancy and 42% reported onset in the months after delivery (Ortonne et al., 2009). It can fade postpartum but often needs treatment for full clearance.</p></div>
             </div>
             <div class="faq__item">
               <button class="faq__question" aria-expanded="false">Can I use retinol during pregnancy?</button>
-              <div class="faq__answer"><p>No. Retinoids are not safe in pregnancy. Focus on strict sun protection during pregnancy; treat post-delivery.</p></div>
+              <div class="faq__answer"><p>Oral retinoids are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy. Topical retinoids have minimal skin absorption and aren't proven human developmental toxicants, but because large controlled pregnancy safety trials are lacking, most guidance still recommends avoiding them as a precaution (Chien et al., 2016) — focus on strict sun protection during pregnancy and treat pigmentation post-delivery. See our <a href="/blog/melasma-in-pregnancy-chloasma">full evidence review</a>.</p></div>
             </div>
 
           </div>
